commentaries.commentary:
9. Negation is fourfold: antecedent negation;
destructive negation; absolute negation and mutual
negation.

15. The subject in which the existence of the thing
to be proved is known for certain is the similar instance;
eg a hearth in the same case.

16. The subject in which the non-existence of the
thing to be proved is determined is the contrary instance;
eg a lake in the same inference.

17. The defective reasons are five (a) straying;
(b) adverse; (c) antithetical; (d) unestablished; and
(e) stultified.

19. Inherence is the eternal relation; it exists in
an inseparable pair: when, between two things, one
thing, as long as it is not destroyed, exists in the
other thing only, they are known as inseparable pairs;
for example, part and the whole; quality and the qualified;
motion and the moving object; genus and the individual;
and particular and the eternal substance.
